				<div class="postbody">
				Since we're talking about religion again, I though I'd feel out the board members on this topic:  Are Mormons (and the Church of Later-Day Saints) a clut, or a religion (and is there a difference)?
<br />

<br />
I never knew a whole lot about Mormonism.  Just started to look into it recently and I have to say that while I'm a very tolerant person, some mormon thoughs are just way, WAY the @#%$ out there.  My investigations were inspired by a pamphlet left on my door by Random_Mormon01 last week.
<br />

<br />
</span><table width="90%" cellspacing="1" cellpadding="3" border="0" align="center"><tr> 	  <td><span class="genmed"><b>Quote:</b></span></td>	</tr>	<tr>	  <td class="quote">Here is the first page:  "Out of all the millions of people in the world, I held it a privilege to be one of those born into a Mormon home.  I cherished my Mormon heritge, treasuirng it asone of the most precious apsects of my life.  I thougth I swas very special to God, because he had placed me into a family who belong to "the one true church," and I knew this put me ahead of many people in my advancement towards my bdecoming a goddes and queen over my own world.
<br />

<br />
I started attending church as an infant, and recieved my name and blessing by the hand of my father when I was three months old.  The only religious training I had was the teching of the Church of Jesus Christ of latter-Day saints.
<br />

<br />
As a Mormon, I was taught that there were many gods, but we served the god of this world, whose name was Eloheim.  Eloheim lived on a planet near the star called Kolob.  He was once a mortal man, who through obedience to Mormon laws and ordinances exalted himself to the status of godhood, just like his father before him and his fater before him, to eternity past.  </td>	</tr></table><span class="postbody">
<br />

<br />
I've talked about trying to be tolerant of other people's beliefs...but Yikes.  This sounds to much like an episode of X-files for me.<br />
				<span class="gensmall"></span><br />
				</div>
			</td></tr>
