			<tr><td colspan="2">
				<div class="postbody">
				Most Mormons I've talked with that were arguing in favor of their religion weren't familiar with any of the Mormon doctrine beyond the Book of Mormon, and The Pearl of Great Price to a lesser extent.  The Book of Mormon is seemingly Christian based(or based off the same beliefs as the bible for those who believe it is a Christian faith), but when looking at other Mormon doctrine many "non-Christian" beliefs are taught.  As I see it and from my experience, many "Mormons" do not believe in actual Mormonism, as they aren't even aware of the full beliefs of the religion(the history of Mormon prophesy or Mormon doctrine beyond the Book of Mormon).  I actually did spend quite a while reading through Mormon doctrine, so that I'd have legitimate excuses to dismiss this set of beliefs.
<br />

<br />
In the book of Mormon you can find:
<br />

<br />
</span><table width="90%" cellspacing="1" cellpadding="3" border="0" align="center"><tr> 	  <td><span class="genmed"><b>Quote:</b></span></td>	</tr>	<tr>	  <td class="quote">ALMA 11:28. Now Zeezrom said: Is there more than one God?
<br />

<br />
ALMA 11:29. And he answered, No.
<br />

<br />
ALMA 11:30. Now Zeezrom said unto him again: How knowest thou these things?
<br />

<br />
ALMA 11:31. And he said: An angel hath made them known unto me.
<br />
</td>	</tr></table><span class="postbody">
<br />

<br />
But we also see this as a direct quote from Joseph Smith in the Journal of Discourses:
<br />

<br />

<br />
</span><table width="90%" cellspacing="1" cellpadding="3" border="0" align="center"><tr> 	  <td><span class="genmed"><b>Quote:</b></span></td>	</tr>	<tr>	  <td class="quote">
<br />
"Hence, the doctrine of a plurality of Gods is as prominent in the Bible as any other doctrine. It is all over the face of the Bible . . . Paul says there are Gods many and Lords many . . . but to us there is but one God--that is pertaining to us; and he is in all and through all" (History of the Church, Vol. 6, page 474). "In the beginning, the head of the Gods called a council of the Gods; and they came together and concocted a plan to create the world and people it." (Journal of Discourses, Vol. 6, p. 5).
<br />
</td>	</tr></table><span class="postbody">
<br />

<br />
A clear contradiction.
<br />

<br />

<br />

<br />

<br />
Also, we see from the Second Book of Nephi, ch. 28:
<br />
</span><table width="90%" cellspacing="1" cellpadding="3" border="0" align="center"><tr> 	  <td><span class="genmed"><b>Quote:</b></span></td>	</tr>	<tr>	  <td class="quote">
<br />
23 Yea, they are grasped with death, and hell; and death, and hell, and the devil, and all that have been seized therewith must stand before the throne of God, and be judged according to their works, from whence they must go into the place prepared for them, even a lake of fire and brimstone, which is <span style="font-weight: bold">endless</span> torment.
<br />
</td>	</tr></table><span class="postbody">
<br />

<br />
Yet many Mormons will argue that hell does not exist, and for those who do you can find in the Articles of Faith(I don't know exactly where, and I can't find it right now) that hell is not eternal.  According to the Second book of Nephi(Mormon doctrine) it is, though.
<br />

<br />

<br />

<br />
I found infinitely more contradictions than this between the Bible vs Mormon doctrine, Mormon doctrine vs Mormon history, and Mormon doctrine vs Mormon doctrine.
<br />

<br />

<br />

<br />
P.S. -  I've never judged the nature of a person based on their religion.  My girlfriend of two years is Mormon(more of a "liberal Mormon", I suppose).  I have nothing against Mormon people(or any other religion, race, sex, etc.  for that matter), as from my experience most are good natured, caring people.  The flaw I see is that they aren't educated in the contradiction behind their religion.  On the occassion that my girlfriend and I(or missionaries, people at school, people at work, etc.) debate Mormon faith she/they are generally not aware of half the points I bring up, or they have no argument/comment for them.
<br />

<br />
I think everyone has a right to their beliefs, but I also feel that people should be educated in those beliefs.  If you're not educated in your beliefs and the beliefs you're arguing against your opinions have virtually no validity to me.<br />
				<span class="gensmall"><br /><br />Last edited by AoWtho on Mon Mar 21, 2005 11:37 am; edited 2 times in total</span><br />
				</div>
			</td></tr>
		</table>
