			<tr><td colspan="2"><hr /></td></tr>
			<tr><td colspan="2">
				<div class="postbody">
				</span><table width="90%" cellspacing="1" cellpadding="3" border="0" align="center"><tr> 	  <td><span class="genmed"><b>Quote:</b></span></td>	</tr>	<tr>	  <td class="quote">Since we're talking about religion again, I though I'd feel out the board members on this topic: Are Mormons (and the Church of Later-Day Saints) a clut, or a religion (and is there a difference)?</td>	</tr></table><span class="postbody">
<br />
In my opinion, there isn't a difference.  Cult = small religion.  Religion = large cult.
<br />

<br />
</span><table width="90%" cellspacing="1" cellpadding="3" border="0" align="center"><tr> 	  <td><span class="genmed"><b>Quote:</b></span></td>	</tr>	<tr>	  <td class="quote">I never knew a whole lot about Mormonism. Just started to look into it recently and I have to say that while I'm a very tolerant person, some mormon thoughs are just way, WAY the @#%$ out there. My investigations were inspired by a pamphlet left on my door by Random_Mormon01 last week. </td>	</tr></table><span class="postbody">
<br />
All religions have their crazy fringe.  Fundamentalist Young-Earth Biblical Literalists?  Suicide-Bombing Martyrs and their host of virgins in the afterlife?  Revelations-fanatics trying to push world events to bring about the Rapture and the Second Coming?
<br />

<br />
I grew up in a Mormon household.  The sci-fi "Kolob" story isn't taught in Church, Sunday School, or Seminary (see below for explanation).  I never even heard the Kolob stuff until long after I'd left the church.  What is taught is something like this phrase: "As man is, God once was.  As God is, man can become."  One of the Mormon Prophets came up with that, I think.
<br />

<br />
What is not specified is if it means God as in "Heavenly Father" (the way Mormons <span style="font-style: italic">usually</span> refer to "God") or God as in the traditional Jesus portion of the holy trinity.  As far as I know, a fringe has taken it and ran with the "Heavenly Father" meaning.  If you take it the other way, it jives with the resurrection/afterlife/the rapture, etc.
<br />

<br />
If you have ever seen the Mormon episode of South Park, it sums up the entire religion.  They don't care that some of their dogma seems wacky to outsiders.  The primary focus of the church is on maintaining a healthy family.  The secondary focus is on maintaining a healthy community.
<br />

<br />
That's the acid test.  Who cares what a person believes as long as it helps them be a moral individual and a productive member of society?  I don't.
<br />

<br />
My only major issues with religious people are: 
<br />
1) Most of them have an "Ours is the only true way" philosophy that fosters rampant religious bigotry.
<br />
2) Their insistence that you <span style="font-style: italic">cannot</span> be a moral person without their unique brand of God.  That all people are inherently evil, and theirs is the only way to salvation.
<br />

<br />
----
<br />

<br />
*Mormon "Seminary" is 4 years of study alongside High School, broken up into year-long segments on the Old Testament, New Testament, Book of Mormon, and Doctrine &amp; Covenants/Pearl of Great Price.<br />
